### Method Overriding

Method overriding occurs when a subclass provides a specific implementation of a method already defined in its parent class.

---

### Rules for Overriding

| Rule | Description |
|------|-------------|
| Same signature | Same name, parameters, and return type |
| Covariant return | Subtype of original return type allowed |
| Access level | Cannot be more restrictive |
| Checked exceptions | Cannot throw broader checked exceptions |
| Final methods | Cannot be overridden |
| Static methods | Not overridden (method hiding) |
| Private methods | Not overridden |

---

### The @Override Annotation

```java
class Animal {
    void makeSound() {
        System.out.println("Some sound");
    }
}

class Cat extends Animal {
    @Override
    void makeSound() {
        System.out.println("Meow");
    }
}
```

The `@Override` annotation tells the compiler you intend to override. It will flag an error if the method doesn't correctly override.

---

### Covariant Return Type

```java
class Parent {
    Parent getInstance() { return this; }
}

class Child extends Parent {
    @Override
    Child getInstance() { return this; }  // Child (subtype) is allowed
}
```

> **Key Point:** Overriding is different from overloading. Overriding is at runtime (dynamic polymorphism), while overloading is at compile time. Always use `@Override` annotation to catch errors early.

codeExample:
class Vehicle {
    void start() {
        System.out.println("Vehicle starting");
    }
}

class Car extends Vehicle {
    @Override
    void start() {
        System.out.println("Car engine starting with key");
    }
}

class Bike extends Vehicle {
    @Override
    void start() {
        System.out.println("Bike kick-starting");
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Vehicle v1 = new Car();
        Vehicle v2 = new Bike();
        v1.start();  // Car version
        v2.start();  // Bike version
    }
}
